<P>Let the durations of war and peace be as <HI>t</HI> to <HI>n,</HI> the &s;um of money borrowed during a war be <HI>ts,</HI> what revenue <HI>(x)</HI> continued from the be|ginning of a war of <HI>t</HI> years, will di&s;charge the whole in <HI>t</HI>&plus;<HI>n</HI> years, &s;o that a nation may pro|bably expect to begin the next war without a debt?</P>
<P><PB N="120" REF="121">Here the annual extraordinary grants in the time of war&equals;<HI>s;</HI> the pre&s;ent value of all the&s;e grants at the end of <HI>t</HI>&plus;<HI>n</HI> years will be, put^g <HI>r</HI>&equals;the amount of 1l. in a year.</P>
<P><GAP DESC="math"></P>
<P>Call <HI>v</HI> the pre&s;ent value of an annuity of 1l. for <HI>t</HI>&plus;<HI>n</HI> years; then <HI>vr^t</HI>^&plus;<HI>^n</HI> &s;hall be the amount of 1l. in <HI>t</HI>&plus;<HI>n</HI> years, an <HI>x</HI> &times; <HI>vr^t</HI>^&plus;<HI>^n</HI> the amount of the required additional revenue &equals; A; then <GAP DESC="math">, and putting the ordinary expence&equals;E, we get E &plus; <HI>x</HI> &equals; the total revenue.</P>
<P>Suppo&s;e in the term of peace <HI>n</HI> years, the debt reduced to <HI>ts;</HI> the annuity which would have di&s;charged this in <HI>t</HI>&plus;<HI>n</HI> years &s;hall be <HI>x</HI> &equals; <GAP DESC="math">; let I the intere&s;t of the increa&s;ed debt; then the annual payment &s;hall be E &plus; 1 &plus; <HI>x</HI>: if the additional debt be propo&s;ed to be di&s;charged at the end of the probable term of peace.</P>
<P>And the proportion of expence upon the&s;e two &s;y&s;tems &s;hall be E &plus; <HI>x,</HI> to E &plus; <HI>x</HI> &plus; 1.</P>
